==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|hleapan|hlēapan}}, from {{proto|Germanic|xlaupan}}. Cognate with Dutch {{term|lopen}}, German {{term|laufen||run}}, Old Norse {{term|hlaupa}} (whence Danish {{term|løbe}}, English {{term|lope}}, Swedish {{term|löpa}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|lēp}}, {{IPA|/liːp/}}, {{SAMPA|/li:p/}}
* {{audio|en-us-leap.ogg|Audio (US)}}

* {{rhymes|iːp}}

===Initialism===
'''LEAP'''

# [[w:Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol|Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|leaps|leaping|'''[[leaped]]''', '''[[leapt]]''', or rarely '''[[lope]]'''|'''[[leaped]]''', '''[[leapt]]''', or rarely '''[[lopen]]'''}}

# {{intransitive}} To [[jump]] from one [[location]] to [[another]].
#* {{circa|1450}} anonymous, ''Merlin''
#*: It is grete nede a man to go bak to recouer the better his '''leep'''
#* '''1600''', anonymous, ''The wisdome of Doctor Dodypoll'', act 4
#*: I, I defie thee: wert not thou next him when he '''leapt''' into the Riuer?
#* '''1783''', [[w:Hugh Blair|Hugh Blair]], from the “Illiad” in ''Lectures on Rhetoric and Belles Lettres'', lecture 4, page 65
#*: Th’ infernal monarch rear’d his horrid head, '''Leapt''' from his throne, lest Neptune’s arm should lay His dark dominions open to the day.
#* '''1999''', Ai, ''Vice: New & Selected Poems'', page 78
#*: It is better to '''leap''' into the void.

====Usage notes====
The choice between {{term|leapt}} and {{term|leaped}} is mostly a matter of regional differences: {{term|leapt}} is preferred in British English and {{term|leaped}} in American English. According to research by John Algeo (''British or American English?'', Cambridge, 2006), {{term|leapt}} is used 80% of the time in UK and 32% in the US.

